<BaseLayout title="Frequently Asked Questions | FreelancePricingCalc" description="Answers to common questions about freelance rates, self-employment taxes, overhead costs, and pricing strategy.">
  <h1>Frequently Asked Questions</h1>

  <h2>Why do I need to charge more than my equivalent employee hourly rate?</h2>
  <p>Because your costs are fundamentally different. As a freelancer, you pay the full 15.3% self-employment tax (employees pay only 7.65%), you pay 100% of your health insurance premiums, you fund your own retirement, you bear overhead costs (software, equipment, insurance, accounting), and you spend a significant portion of your time on non-billable activities like business development and administration. If you simply charge what an employee with the same skill set earns per hour, you'll net significantly less after all those costs are accounted for. Our calculator shows you the rate that actually achieves income parity with employment — and it's typically 40–75% higher than the equivalent employee hourly rate.</p>

  <h2>How much should I budget for self-employment taxes?</h2>
  <p>Self-employment tax is 15.3% of your net self-employment income up to the Social Security wage base ($168,600 in 2024), then 2.9% on income above that. You can deduct half of the SE tax from your gross income on your federal return, which reduces your income tax burden slightly. A simple rule of thumb: set aside 25–30% of every payment you receive for taxes (covering SE tax plus federal income tax plus state income tax if applicable). Actual tax liability depends on your total income, deductions, and state — consult a tax professional for a specific estimate.</p>

  <h2>What self-employment expenses are tax deductible?</h2>
  <p>Most ordinary and necessary business expenses are deductible, including: home office (dedicated space used exclusively for business), health insurance premiums (as an adjustment to gross income), retirement plan contributions (SEP-IRA, Solo 401k), professional development and education, software and tools, equipment, professional liability insurance, marketing and advertising, professional services (accounting, legal), and business use of a vehicle. The IRS Publication 334 (Tax Guide for Small Businesses) covers deductions in detail. Working with a CPA who specializes in self-employed clients is typically the most reliable way to maximize legitimate deductions.</p>

  <h2>What is a realistic billable utilization rate?</h2>
  <p>Experienced freelancers typically bill 50–70% of their available working hours. The rest goes to business development, administration, professional development, client communication, and the reality of gaps between projects. New freelancers often bill even less while building their client base. We default to 60% utilization in our calculator, but adjusting it to reflect your actual experience — or your honest expectation — significantly affects the calculated target rate. Higher utilization targets mean lower required rates; lower utilization targets mean higher required rates.</p>

  <h2>Should I be an LLC or a sole proprietor?</h2>
  <p>This is a business structure question with both legal and tax implications that you should discuss with a CPA and/or business attorney. The short version: a sole proprietorship is the default if you do nothing; an LLC adds liability protection in most states with minimal cost and complexity; an S-corp election (for LLCs or corporations) can reduce self-employment tax burden above a certain income level (rough threshold: $40,000+ in net freelance income), but adds complexity and administrative cost. The optimal structure depends on your income level, state laws, and risk profile.</p>

  <h2>How often should I raise my rates?</h2>
  <p>Most financial advisors recommend reviewing and potentially raising freelance rates at least annually. Rate increases should account for inflation, skill and experience growth, changes in market demand for your specialty, and any changes in your cost structure. A 3–5% annual increase is modest and defensible; larger increases (10–25%) may be appropriate when you've significantly increased your capabilities or when your rates have fallen meaningfully below market. Our guide on raising rates without losing clients covers the mechanics of having that conversation.</p>

  <h2>What should I do about clients who negotiate on price?</h2>
  <p>Having a rate framework based on actual cost and income calculations makes negotiating easier, because you can be clear about what you can and cannot accommodate. If a client pushes back on price, the conversation can be: "Here's what's included at this rate. If we need to adjust the budget, let's talk about adjusting the scope." Offering to reduce scope rather than reduce rate protects your rate integrity while giving the client a path to work with you. Always be willing to walk away from work that doesn't support your rate floor — clients who accept rates below your floor are actually expensive clients.</p>

  <h2>Is freelancing financially worth it compared to employment?</h2>
  <p>It depends on your rate, your utilization, and your preferences. At the right rate with reasonable utilization, freelancing can provide significantly higher gross income than employment — the market typically prices independent expertise at a premium because the employer bears no benefits, severance, or management costs. But the equation requires: a rate that actually covers your cost structure (which this calculator helps establish), consistent client demand, and disciplined financial management to handle income variability. Freelancing is financially viable and often financially superior to employment for people with in-demand skills who set their rates correctly from the start.</p>

  <p><em>Informational only. Not professional advice.</em></p>
